kering, Lincolnshire, England","St Gregory Churchyard Sudbury, Babergh District, Suffolk, England":"Sudbury St Gregory, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Sudbury, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sudbury, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Sudbury, Suffolk, England":"Sudbury, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ruggles","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Essex): variant of the now extinct surname <i>Ruggle</i>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. The origin of <i>Ruggle</i> is uncertain. It could be a variant of the Suffolk and Essex name <i>Ricold</i> with voicing of /k/ to /g/ and the same vowel change as seen in <b>Smoothy</b> for   Smithey   (another Suffolk and Essex name) and in <b>Puckering</b> for   Pickering  .","History: The founder of this influential American family was Thomas Ruggles (1584–1644) of Sudbury, Suffolk, England, who settled in Roxbury, MA, in 1637."],"variants":[{"name":"Smithey","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): from Middle English <i>smithi</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old Norse <i>smithja</i>), used either as a topographic name for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, or an occupational name for someone who worked in one. Compare   Smith   and   Smead  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Ruggles was born in 1469, in Holton cum Beckering, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Rogyll Ruggles, was 25 and his mother, Maude Dexter, was 25. He married Mrs William Ruggles in 1498, in Sudbury, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died after 1503, in his hometown, and was buried in Sudbury St Gregory, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1469–after 1503":"1469–pärast 1503","1469–1503":"1469–1503","1470–1525":"1470–1525","1497–1547":"1497–1547","1501–1560":"1501–1560","1503–1547":"1503–1547","1444–1469":"1444–1469","1445–1520":"1445–1520","1560":"1560","1470":"1470","1547":"1547","1525":"1525","1503":"1503","1469":"1469","1501":"1501","after 1503":"pärast 1503","1445":"1445","about 1503":"umbes 1503","1444":"1444","1498":"1498","1520":"1520","1497":"1497","about 1501":"umbes 1501","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Holton-cum-Beckering, Lincolnshire, England":"Holton cum Beckering, Lincolnshire, England","St Gregory Churchyard Sudbury, Babergh District, Suffolk, England":"Sudbury St Gregory, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sudbury, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sudbury, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sudbury, Suffolk, England":"Sudbury, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1469–after 1503":"1469–1503 jälkeen","1469–1503":"1469–1503","1470–1525":"1470–1525","1497–1547":"1497–1547","1501–1560":"1501–1560","1503–1547":"1503–1547","1444–1469":"1444–1469","1445–1520":"1445–1520","1560":"1560","1470":"1470","1547":"1547","1525":"1525","1503":"1503","1469":"1469","1501":"1501","after 1503":"1503 jälkeen","1445":"1445","about 1503":"noin 1503","1444":"1444","1498":"1498","1520":"1520","1497":"1497","about 1501":"noin 1501","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Holton-cum-Beckering, Lincolnshire, England":"Holton cum Beckering, Lincolnshire, England","St Gregory Churchyard Sudbury, Babe